DESCRIPTION:Image credits: BM Archives \n\nJoin architect Priya Joseph for a presentation on River Netravati in Karnataka. This presentation is about a playful but political understanding of the context of an ecologically sensitive area—the banks River Netravati in Karnataka. \n\nThe studio work pushed the conventional notions of using art\, drawings\, cartography and mapping to understand the Anthropocene. It drew on the latent of the digital and the familiarity of the analogue\, to analyse the industrial ruins left by humans\, the river and its relationship to its soil and making\, the slow disturbances on the ecological balance\, the material and human.
DTEND:20260421T133000Z
DTSTART:20260421T123000Z
SUMMARY:Slow Disturbances: Terracotta Making Along the Rivers of South India
UID:1246@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/slow-disturbances-terracotta-making-along-the-rivers-of-south-india/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-02T115801.359.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260408T045556Z
DESCRIPTION:Join artist afra eisma\, in conversation with Dr. Gita Chadha and unpack the making of warrior garments. Explore the ideas contained within the artworks\, what it means to centre sexual violence and personal trauma through art\, and the precarity of talking about it across nations and institutions. Discover the contours of afra’s practice\, the people and art that inspires them\, and the hope they carry for the future in these dark times. 
DTEND:20260412T123000Z
DTSTART:20260412T110000Z
SUMMARY:In Focus: afra eisma
UID:1243@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/in-focus-afra-eisma/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-01T161439.576.png
CATEGORIES:Kids & Family,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260406T093857Z
DESCRIPTION:Spend the summer inside a museum\, learning from professional artists. Our workshops for children aged 8–12 are hands-on\, creative\, and fun\, covering everything from tie-dye to ceramics and more. \n\nChoose your experience\n\nRegister for individual workshops\, or go all-in with our combination ticket for access to every session throughout the camp.\n\nMay 4\n\nCeramics and Mask Making Workshop\n\nMay 5\n\nAnthotype and Cyanotype Workshop\n\nMay 6\n\nCanvas City\n\nMay 7\n\nGrowing From Nothing: A Gardening Walk Workshop\n\nMay 8\n\nNatural Tie-Dye Workshop\n\nEnd-of-camp showcase\n\nThe final day is a celebration where the participants present everything they made over the summer\, open for all families to attend.\n\nNote: \n\n-Please pack a lunch\, snacks\, and a water bottle for your child each day.\n\n-Every registered participant receives a gift store voucher of equal value\, redeemable at the MAP Gift Store. \n\n-If you're a working parent\, our café space is open for you to use while your child is in session.\n\nThese workshops are for children between the ages of 8-12. If you are between the ages of 13-16 check out our programme here.\n\nSpots are limited. Register early to secure your place.
DTEND:20260509T103000Z
DTSTART:20260504T043000Z
SUMMARY:Summer at MAP (Ages 8-12)
UID:1239@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/summer-at-map-ages-8-12/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/image-7.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260409T102526Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Manasi Mudvikar\n\nA public engagement workshop inspired by the book “My Neighbour is a Pest” curated by Timbuktoo Young Writers. The workshop invites intergenerational participants to recall\, share and document the urban biodiversity of the neighbourhood and how life once changed with seasons\, as compared to the present. \n\nGiven the ravages of time and climate change\, we no longer recall houses and neighbourhoods by their flora\, fauna and fruit. Addresses once were associated with bougainvilleas and mango or jackfruit trees. The seasons would influence the vegetables we ate and the ritual of changing clothing. Nature’s produce would ripen to suit the body’s seasonal demands. The workshop will document these stories in flux via illustration and sensory-based storytelling—mixing memory\, ritual and the lyricism of seasonal change.
DTEND:20260418T063000Z
DTSTART:20260418T043000Z
SUMMARY:Where have all the sparrows gone?
UID:1236@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/where-have-all-the-sparrows-gone/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-08T101551.202.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260408T082314Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Rustam Vania\n\nAt the top of the high-altitude Himalayan ranges lives the snow leopard\, elusive and solitary\, known as the ghost of the mountains. To protect it is to protect the fragile world it moves through. \n\nThis illustrated talk and interactive workshop takes you into that world\, tracing the delicate balance between human livelihoods\, conservation\, and the restoration of Himalayan ecosystems.\n\n&nbsp\;\n\nPlease note the interactive workshop has a few slots and requires registration. The illustrated talk\, open for all\, is from 7:00 PM to 8:30 PM.
DTEND:20260505T150000Z
DTSTART:20260505T123000Z
SUMMARY:The Ghosts of Conservation - Political Ecology of High Altitude Himalayan Landscapes
UID:1248@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/the-ghosts-of-conservation-political-ecology-of-high-altitude-himalayan-landscapes/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-02T112617.763.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260408T045758Z
DESCRIPTION:Five days\, a museum full of inspiration\, and a workshop unlike any other\, join film maker Hansa Thapliyal for doll-making and stop-motion animation at MAP.\n\nUsing the museum as a creative playground\, participants will work with everyday materials and scraps to build their own dolls\, drawing inspiration from our exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. Along the way\, they'll explore their ideas\, experiment with storytelling\, and find their own creative voice.\n\nThrough playful stop-motion exercises\, these ideas will begin to move\, building into a collaborative animated film screened at the end of Summer at MAP.\n\nParticipants are required to bring:\n\n-A mobile phone with a camera\n\n-A few discarded items from home to add a personal touch to the creations\n\nNote: \n\n-Please pack a lunch\, snacks\, and a water bottle for your child each day.\n\n-Every registered participant receives a gift store voucher of equal value\, redeemable at the MAP Gift Store. \n\n-If you're a working parent\, our café space is open for you to use while your child is in session.\n\nThese workshops are for children between the ages of 13-16 If you are between the ages of 8-12 check out our programme here.\n\nSpots are limited. Register early to secure your place.
DTEND:20260516T103000Z
DTSTART:20260511T043000Z
SUMMARY:Summer at MAP (Ages 13-16)
UID:1240@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/summer-at-map-ages-13-16/
